We can apply the CYK algorithm.  First, the only non‐terminals that produce the individual terminals are

  t35→NT30  
  t153→NT14  
  t45→NT110  
  t118→NT26  
  t89→NT116  

so at positions 1…8 we have
 1:{30} 2:{14} 3:{110} 4:{26} 5:{116} 6:{116} 7:{26} 8:{116}.

Next we look for rules A→BC combining each adjacent pair.  Checking all binary rules, none has B/C matching any of 
 (30,14), (14,110), (110,26), (26,116), (116,116), (116,26) or (26,116).  Hence no nonterminal derives any length‐2 substring, and consequently no longer spans can be built up to S.

Therefore the string is not in L(G).

  t102 t32 t102 t98 t19 t19 t98 t142 t89 t48 t123 t98 t48 t48.

In fact no sequence of splits under either S→NT82 NT76 or S→NT5 NT81 can derive all 19 leaves.  Therefore the string is not in the language.

we see that NT76 has no productions of its own (no “NT76 → …” rule), so the only way to derive is

Whichever way NT81 expands (NT81 → NT92 NT97 or NT81 → NT34 NT55), its final terminal cannot be “t48” (the only nonterminal that produces “t48” is NT67, and NT67 never appears as the rightmost leaf of an NT81 derivation). Thus no matter how you split the 20‐token string between NT5 and NT81, you cannot end in t48 under NT81. Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.

t120 t9 t19 t123 t45 t135 t136 t32 t9 t89 t89 t89 t136 t148 t19 t35 t148 t15 t45 t142 t153 t9 t9 t123

and similarly the preceding tokens fit into the recursive binary expansion of NT112, NT33, NT70, NT42, etc.  Since all terminal‐to‐nonterminal matches occur and the binary splits line up to cover the full length, the grammar does indeed generate the entire string.
